Astro photography is one of the most challenging things I’ve ever done, so much technical information to take in, everything has to be so precise and exact, no room for error.  Ran into a multitude of issues last night but was able to squeeze out a few frames to stack.  This is the lagoon nebula tucked away in the galactic core of our own Milky Way galaxy. 4,077 light years away from our beautiful little home we call Earth. For reference, if you traveled at highway speeds (80 mph) it would take you 32 billion years to get to this nebula.

The Eagle nebula. (Messier 16) has always sparked my interest since I was a kid, and saw the Hubble picture of this nebula.  The nebula itself has a vast radius of 60 light years.  Inside the nebula is home to the famous “pillars of creation” a dense gas and dust formation that births new stars.  The pillars them selves stretch a massive 5 light years in distance.  This nebula is about 5700 light years away from earth, and is only visible through telescopes.  At 80 mph it would take you 47 billion years to reach this nebula.

The eastern veil nebula, a gas remnant from an exploded star (supernova). The source supernova was a star 20 times more massive than the Sun which exploded between 10,000 and 20,000 years ago.  At the time of the explosion, the supernova would have appeared brighter than Venus in the sky, and visible in the daytime.  This nebula is 2400 light years away from Earth and is primarily made up of hydrogen and oxygen iii gas.
.
#nasa #astrophotography #nebula #jwsttelescope #hubble #askar #zwo #asiair

The western veil nebula is a mix of hyrdrofen, oxygen, and sulfur gas from an exploded star (supernova) from about 10-15 thousand years ago.  I’ve learned so much about Astro photography in the past couple months my head hurts.

The North American nebula.  The North America Nebula covers a region more than ten times the area of the full moon, but its surface brightness is low, so normally it cannot be seen with the unaided eye.  The portion of the nebula resembling Mexico and Central America is known as the Cygnus Wall.  This region exhibits the most concentrated star formation. The entire HII region Sh2-117 is estimated to be 140 light years across, and the North America nebula stretches 90 light years north to south.  The nebula itself is about 2,590 light years away from Earth.
.

The heart nebula is an emission nebula, 7500 light years away from Earth and located in the Perseus Arm of the Galaxy in the constellation Cassiopeia. It was discovered by William Herschel on 3 November 1787.  It displays glowing ionized hydrogen gas and darker dust lanes.
.
.

The Funny Thing About DREAMS- when we’re little we lie in bed and think about all the things we want to do SOMEDAY.  We get inspired and influened by those we look up to and we say....”I’m gonna do something like THAT when I grow up.”

We get ourselves so excited that we just CAN’T WAIT for the moment where and when it all comes together.

And then life sets in.  Problems arise.  Reality is harder than what our dreams made it out to be.  People tell us our dreams are stupid and unattainable anyways.  We wanted the freedom of being an adult without realizing the obligations of what being one truly meant. 

So slowly but surely, like sand sifting through our fingers....we watch our dreams fade away.  And we accept that our dreams weren’t real anyways, and that we didn’t deserve to have them.  It’s time to grow up, accept my reality, and let go of my dreams. 

We trade in wonder for mediocrity and we settle for less than what we dreamed of as a little boy or girl.  And now when we close our eyes we no longer dream...we just pray that we can make it to the next day.

Just writing that last paragraph brought tears to my eyes.  Because it’s so heartbreaking...and it’s also untrue for those who are willing to FIGHT for their DREAMS.

ANYTHING that you are seeking in life will ONLY come to you...if you are willing to put everything on the line to get it.  Your heart, your soul, your tears, your fears, and your determination.

Making a dream come true isn’t supposed to be easy.  And it’s why most people don’t achieve them.  They just give up too early.  They rob themselves of the opportunity to LIVE and sacrifice a life of adventure and amazement for the creature comforts of life.

It’s why I’ve refused to grow up.  Why I’ve refused to give up.  And it’s why I’ll never give up on my dreams.  You can all reach heights you’ve never seen before....but only if you’re willing to give everything you have inside of you to get there.

So when I close my eyes at night as a grown man and I drift towards sleep, the little boy in me takes over and dreams.  And then I wake up in the morning and do everything in my power to make ti a reality. 

NEVER, give up on your dreams....

The Lagoon and Trifid Nebulas, with a little patience and trial and error I was able to frame up two beautiful nebulas in one image.

The Lagoon Nebula is a giant interstellar cloud in the constellation Sagittarius. It is classified as an emission nebula and as an H II region. The Lagoon Nebula was discovered by Giovanni Hodierna before 1654 and is one of only two star-forming nebulae faintly visible to the eye from mid-northern latitudes.

The Trifid Nebula is an H II region in the north-west of Sagittarius in a star-forming region in the Milky Way's Scutum-Centaurus Arm.  It was discovered by Charles Messier on June 5, 1764.  Its name means 'three-lobe'. The object is an unusual combination of an open cluster of stars, an emission nebula (the relatively dense, reddish-pink portion), a reflection nebula (the mainly NNE blue portion), and a dark nebula (the apparent 'gaps' in the former that cause the trifurcated appearance.

Thes nebulas are about 4000 light years away from Earth.
.

The Pacman Nebula.  The nebula is a bright emission nebula and part of an H II region in the northern constellation of Cassiopeia and is part of the Milky Way's Perseus Spiral Arm. Colloquially, NGC 281 is also known as the Pacman Nebula for its resemblance to the video game character.
.

The Elephant Trunk Nebula.

The Elephant's Trunk Nebula is a concentration of interstellar gas and dust within the much larger ionized gas region IC 1396 located in the constellation Cepheus about 2,400 light years away from Earth. The piece of the nebula shown here is the dark, dense globule IC 1396A; it is commonly called the Elephant's Trunk nebula because of its appearance at visible light wavelengths, where there is a dark patch with a bright, sinuous rim. The bright rim is the surface of the dense cloud that is being illuminated and ionized by a very bright, massive star (HD 206267) that is just to the east of IC 1396A.  The Elephant's Trunk Nebula is now thought to be a site of star formation, containing several very young (less than 100,000 yr) stars that were discovered in infrared images in 2003. Two older (but still young, a couple of million years, by the standards of stars, which live for billions of years) stars are present in a small, circular cavity in the head of the globule. Winds from these young stars may have emptied the cavity.
.

The soul nebula.  An emission nebula located in Cassiopeia.  Several small open clusters are embedded in the nebula: CR 34, 632, and 634 (in the head) and IC 1848 (in the body). This nebula is about 5000 light years away.

The Orion Nebula (also known as Messier 42, M42, or NGC 1976) is a diffuse nebula situated in the Milky Way, being south of Orion's Belt in the constellation of Orion, and is known as the middle "star" in the "sword" of Orion. It is one of the brightest nebulae and is visible to the naked eye in the night sky with apparent magnitude 4.0. It is 1,344 ± 20 light-years (412.1 ± 6.1 pc) away and is the closest region of massive star formation to Earth. The M42 nebula is estimated to be 24 light-years across (so its apparent size from Earth is approximately 1 degree). It has a mass of about 2,000 times that of the Sun. Older texts frequently refer to the Orion Nebula as the Great Nebula in Orion or the Great Orion Nebula.
.
.

The greatAndromeda Galaxy is a barred spiral galaxy and is the nearest major galaxy to the Milky Way. It was originally named the Andromeda Nebula and is cataloged as Messier 31, M31, and NGC 224. Andromeda has a diameter of about 46.56 kiloparsecs (152,000 light-years) and is approximately 765 kpc (2.5 million light-years) from Earth. The galaxy's name stems from the area of Earth's sky in which it appears, the constellation of Andromeda, which itself is named after the princess who was the wife of Perseus in Greek mythology. 
.
.

The Pleiades star cluster also known as the Seven Sisters, Messier 45, and other names by different cultures, is an asterism and an open star cluster containing middle-aged, hot B-type stars in the north-west of the constellation Taurus. At a distance of about 444 light years, it is among the nearest star clusters to Earth. It is the nearest Messier object to Earth, and is the most obvious cluster to the naked eye in the night sky. It is also observed to house the reflection nebula NGC 1432, an HII region.
.
.

The flaming star nebula.  The nebula measures approximately 37.0' x 19.0', and lies about 1,500 light-years away from Earth.  It is believed that the proper motion of the central star can be traced back to the Orion's Belt area.  The nebula is about 5 light-years across.  IC 405 (also known as the Flaming Star Nebula, SH 2-229, or Caldwell 31) is an emission and reflection nebula. in the constellation Auriga north of the celestial equator, surrounding the bluish, irregular variable star AE Aurigae.
.
.

The crescent nebula an emission nebula in the constellation Cygnus, about 5000 light-years away from Earth. It was discovered by William Herschel in 1792.  It is formed by the fast stellar wind from the Wolf-Rayet star WR 136 (HD 192163) colliding with and energizing the slower moving wind ejected by the star when it became a red giant around 250,000 to 400,000 years ago. The result of the collision is a shell, and two shock waves, one moving outward and one moving inward. The inward moving shock wave heats the stellar wind to X-ray-emitting temperatures.
.
.

The Pelican Nebula (also known as IC 5070 and IC 5067, is an H II region associated with the North America Nebula in the constellation Cygnus. The gaseous contortions of this emission nebula bear a resemblance to a pelican, giving rise to its name.  The Pelican Nebula is located nearby first magnitude star Deneb, and is divided from its more prominent neighbor, the North America Nebula, by a foreground molecular cloud filled with dark dust.  Both are part of the larger H II region of Westerhout 40.  This is only a small portion of the nebula,  and I processed it highlight different gasses in different colors.
.

I’ve been really looking forward to shooting this target ever since I started doing Astro photography 4 months ago.  I processed this nebula in HSO.  It’s called the rosette nebula, also known as Caldwell 49) A large H II region located near one end of a giant molecular cloud in the Monoceros region of the Milky Way Galaxy. The open cluster NGC 2244 (Caldwell 50) is closely associated with the nebulosity, the stars of the cluster having been formed from the nebula's matter.  The nebula has been noted to be having a shape reminiscent of a human skull, and is sometimes referred to as the "Skull Nebula." It is 5200 light years away from Earth, and is 62 light years in diameter.  Time and distance is a very relative and hard thing to wrap our heads around.  To us on Earth 100mph is pretty fast, but even if we hopped aboard the space shuttle discovery, which can travel 5 miles a second, it would take us about 37,200 years to go one light-year.  Multiply that number by 5200 and that’s how many years it would take us to reach this nebula screaming across space at 5 miles per second.
.
.

The Seagull Nebula (also known as IC 2177) is a relatively bright, and very large emission nebula found between the constellations Monoceros and Canis Major.  Amateur astronomers and astrophotographers often refer to this emission region as the Seagull Nebula, even though it actually encompasses a much larger area including star clusters, dust clouds, and reflection nebulae.  The full extent of the nebula’s wings spread out over 100 light-years, which some say, resembles a seagull in flight.

I processed this nebula in the Hubble SHO color pallete to seperate the different gases more definitively and also processed it in typical rgb.

The bubble and lobster claw nebulas.

The bubble nebula is near a giant molecular cloud which contains the expansion of the bubble nebula while itself being excited by the hot central star, causing it to glow.  It was discovered in November 1787 by William Herschel.

The lobster claw nebula contains many proto-stars shielded by dark discs of gas, and young stars wrapped in expanding "cocoons" or expanding gases surrounding these small stars. It is also known as the Lobster Nebula.  This nebula was given the name War and Peace Nebula by the Midcourse Space Experiment scientists because of its appearance, which, in infrared images the bright, western part resembles a dove, while the eastern part looks like a skull.  A petition by anime fans to rename it as the Madokami nebula, due to resemblance with a character, was unsuccessful.

Jellyfish Nebula in HOO.

IC 443 is a galactic supernova remnant in the constellation Gemini. On the plane of the sky, it is located near the star Eta Geminorum. Its distance is roughly 5,000 light years from Earth. IC 443 may be the remains of a supernova that occurred 3,000 - 30,000 years ago.

The Triangulum Galaxy is a spiral galaxy 2.73 million light-years from Earth in the constellation Triangulum. It is catalogued as Messier 33 or NGC598. With the D25 isophotal diameter of 18.74 kiloparsecs (61,100 light-years), the Triangulum Galaxy is the third-largest member of the Local Group of galaxies, behind the Andromeda Galaxy and the Milky Way.

Happy holidays everyone.

This nebula and star cluster is call the Christmas tree cluster and the cone nebula.

The Cone Nebula is an H II region in the constellation of Monoceros. It was discovered by William Herschel on December 26, 1785, at which time he designated it H V.27. The nebula is located about 2,700 light-years away from Earth. The Cone Nebula forms part of the nebulosity surrounding the Christmas Tree Cluster. The designation of NGC 2264 in the New General Catalogue refers to both objects and not the nebula alone.
.
